The Refinery evaluates contractor safety programs and performance during the selection of a contractor.  The Refinery uses "PICS" (Pacific Industrial Contractor Screening), a third party consulting company who evaluates and monitors contractor qualifications and safety records.  Contractors are to be approved by PICS before they enter the Refinery.  Refinery personnel periodically monitor contractor performance through job site audits and PICS reports to ensure that contractors are fulfilling their safety obligations.  The information and data from the audits is communicated to contractors to facilitate continuous improvement.  The Eagles (behavioral based safety program) also conduct observations of contractors. 



CHEMICAL-SPECIFIC PREVENTION STEPS



The processes at the Kenai refinery have hazards that must be managed to ensure continued safe operation.  The accident prevention program summarized previously is applied to all EPA RMP-covered processes at the Kenai refinery.  Collectively, these prevention program activities help prevent potential accident scenarios that could be caused by equipment failures or human errors. 



In addition to the accident prevention program activities, the Refinery has safety features on many units to help contain and control a release, quickly detect a release, and reduce the consequences of (mitigate) a release.  The following types of safety features are used in various processes:



Release Detection

?    Portable hydrocarbon detectors;

?    Heat, smoke, and flame detectors;

?    Gas and toxic detectors for control rooms and the laboratory; and 

?    H2S detectors for the sulfur unit and the API area.



Release Containment

 and Control

?    Process relief valves that discharge to a flare to capture and incinerate episodic releases;

?    Valves to permit isolation of the process (manual or automated);

?    Automated shutdown systems for specific process parameters (e.g., high level, high temperature);

?    Vessel to permit partial removal of the process inventory in the event of a release (e.g., a dump tank);

?    Curbing or diking to contain liquid releases;

?    Redundant equipment and instrumentation (e.g., uninterruptible power supply for process control system backup firewater pump); and

?    Atmospheric relief devices.



Release Mitigation

?    Fire suppression and extinguishing systems;

?    Deluge system for specific equipment;

?    Trained emergency response personnel;

?    Personal protective equipment (e.g., protective clothing, self-contained breathing apparatus); and

?    Blast-resistant buildings to help protect control systems and personnel.



EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM INFORMATION



The Kenai Refinery maintains a written emergency response program, which is in place to protect worker and public safety as well as the environment.  The program consists of procedures for responding to a release of a regulated substance, including the possibility of a fire or explosion if a flammable substance is accidentally released.  The procedures address all aspects of emergency response, including proper first aid and medical treatment for exposures, evacuation plans and accounting for personnel after an evacuation, notification of local emergency response agencies and the public if a release occurs, and post-incident cleanup and decontamination requirements.  The Refinery has procedures that address maintenance, inspection, and testing of emergency response equipment, as well as instructions that address the use of emergency response equipment.  Employees receive training in these procedures as necessary to perform their specific emergency response duties.  The emergency response program is updated when

necessary based on modifications made to refinery processes or other refinery facilities.



The overall emergency response program for the Refinery is coordinated with local emergency responders, such as the fire department and the office of the Alaska State Troopers, as well as state and federal agencies.  The Refinery has around-the-clock communications capability with appropriate community officials and emergency response organizations.  This provides a means of facilitating quick response to an incident, as well as notifying the public of an incident if necessary.  The Refinery conducts periodic emergency response exercises that involve refinery personnel, contractors, and emergency response organizations.  The refinery provides refresher training to emergency responders regarding their responsibilities during an emergency.



PLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY



Tesoro's accident prevention program elements often generate recommendations to address safety hazards, reduce risks, and/or reduce exposure in case releases occur.  Each recommendation is tracked until it is completely resolved.  Some of the recommendations become major process projects that can only be completed during plant turnarounds.  The Refinery has several projects planned/in progress to improve safety:



(1)    Expand plant air system capacity to improve process control and reliability;

(2)    New facility for cleaning equipment and handling hazardous waste;

(3)    Safety Instrumented System (SIS) expansion for protection of identified fired heaters;

(4)    Installation of upgraded tank level gauging system; and

(5)    2018 Partial Recycle Isomerization Process High Temperature Hydrogen Attack (HTHA) equipment replacement.
